      <abstract displayLabel="Abstract">Public safety practitioners utilizing the forthcoming Nationwide
                Public Safety Broadband Network (NPSBN) will have smartphones, tablets, and
                wearables at their disposal. Although these devices should enable first responders
                to complete their missions, any influx of new technologies will introduce new
                security vulnerabilities. This document analyzes the needs of public safety mobile
                devices and wearables from a cybersecurity perspective, specifically for the fire
                service, emergency medical service (EMS), and law enforcement. To accomplish this
                goal, cybersecurity use cases were analyzed, previously known attacks against
                related systems were reviewed, and a threat model was created. The overarching goal
                of this work is to identify security objectives for these devices, enabling
                jurisdictions to more easily select and purchase secure devices and industry to
                design and build more secure public safety devices.</abstract>
